      "rationale": "Predicted NIH = 0.0041 g/100 L versus measured NIH = 0.0044 ± 0.0006 g/100 L; relative error 6.8%. Acceptance criterion of 15% relative error met. Comparison performed at the nominal design operating point only; the broader COU matrix of five operating conditions is addressed through sensitivity analysis rather than independent experimental validation at each point."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "QoIs used in validation (NIH, wall shear stress) are directly linked to the COU decision metric (relative hemolysis index RH).",
      "rationale": "NIH and area-averaged wall shear stress are the primary inputs to the Giersiepen-Wurzinger power-law damage integral. These QoIs are directly traceable to the RH < 1 acceptance criterion used for the regulatory decision. Relevance of QoIs to COU confirmed."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Validation geometry, fluid, and at least one operating condition match COU device and intended operating envelope.",
      "rationale": "Validation used the FDA generic centrifugal pump geometry identical to the COU device. Blood analog fluid properties matched. The nominal operating point (3.5 L/min, 2400 RPM) falls within the COU operating envelope. The power-law damage model is stated to apply under the condition that RBC damage accumulates linearly across independent stress exposures — a precondition established for steady, low-turbulence regimes. This precondition is satisfied at the nominal validation point. However, the COU spans four additional operating conditions including higher speeds (up to 3200 RPM) and lower flows (2.0 L/min) where recirculation zones and elevated turbulent stresses are present; the linear superposition precondition is not verified for these off-design conditions."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Numerical solver error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 1,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Iterative convergence demonstrated; residual norms below 1e-5 for all transport equations.",
      "rationale": "All steady-state simulations converged to residual norms below 1e-6 for continuity, momentum, and turbulence transport equations. Mass imbalance < 0.01%. Solver error contribution to overall numerical uncertainty is negligible relative to discretization error."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Use error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 1,
      "achievedLevel": 1,
      "factorStatus": "not-assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Not required at MRL 2 for this factor.",
      "rationale": "Use error assessment is not required at Model Risk Level 2 for this factor under ASME V&V 40-2018. Scoped out per MRL 2 assessment matrix."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model form",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Turbulence model selection and hemolysis sub-model formulation documented with justification for applicability to rotating blood pump flows.",
      "rationale": "SST k-omega turbulence model selected based on documented performance for rotating machinery with adverse pressure gradients. Giersiepen-Wurzinger power-law hemolysis model (C = 3.62e-5, alpha = 2.416, beta = 0.785) applied as the damage accumulation integral. Model form is consistent with literature for centrifugal blood pump CFD. The power-law formulation assumes linear superposition of sub-lethal damage events, which is the theoretical precondition underlying the model's applicability. This assumption is explicitly noted in the original Giersiepen et al. (1990) derivation as holding for quasi-steady laminar-dominant shear; its validity at off-design COU conditions with unsteady recirculation has not been evaluated within this assessment package."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model inputs",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Sensitivity analysis performed on key model inputs; inputs with influence > 5% on NIH QoI identified and bounded.",
      "rationale": "One-at-a-time sensitivity analysis performed on inlet velocity profile, fluid viscosity, and rotational speed. Rotational speed showed highest sensitivity (dNIH/dRPM normalized = 0.18). All input uncertainties bounded within ±3% of nominal values based on manufacturing tolerances and test loop instrumentation accuracy. Input uncertainty contribution to NIH uncertainty estimated at ±9%."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test samples",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 1,
      "achievedLevel": 1,
      "factorStatus": "not-assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Not required at MRL 2 for this factor.",
      "rationale": "Test sample characterization beyond standard fluid property documentation is not required at Model Risk Level 2. Assessment scoped out per MRL 2 requirements."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Equivalency of input parameters",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
